cultural influences, ranging from Victorian sentimental art to New Look fashion, from nineteenth-century children’s literature to post-World War II sexology, and from grand opera to 1930s radio comedy. By moving beyond the general category of "woman," Precocious Charms leads to a new understanding of the complex pleasures Hollywood created for its audience during the half century when film stars were a major influence on America’s cultural imagination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChild actorszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aGirls in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTeenage girls in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aactresses.  aamerican culture.  aaudrey hepburn.  achild actors.  achild stars.  acinema studies.  aclassical hollywood.  acultural history.  acultural imagination.  adeanna durbin.  aelizabeth taylor.  afemale stars.  afilm historians.  afilm history.  afilm industry.  afilm scholars.  afilm studies.  agirlhood.  ahistorical.  ahollywood image.  ahollywood women.  ajennifer jones.  amary pickford.  anew look fashion.  apersonas.  asexology.  ashirley temple.  avictorian.  awomen and girls.  ayouthfulness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027424240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095529540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520955295423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520955295/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY